Lab 12: Solutions

  1. These exercises are based on a famous kaggle competition in which competitors predict who lives and who dies on the Titanic. Download the data set from this address, and load it into R. It has the following variables:
  • Survived Survival (0 = No; 1 = Yes)
  • Pclass Passenger Class (1 = 1st; 2 = 2nd; 3 = 3rd)
  • Name Name
  • Sex Sex
  • Age Age (in years)
  • SibSp Number of Siblings/Spouses Aboard
  • Parch Number of Parents/Children Aboard
  • Ticket Ticket Number
  • Fare Passenger Fare
  • Cabin Cabin
  • Embarked Port of Embarkation (C = Cherbourg; Q = Queenstown; S = Southampton)
library(tidyverse)
library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)
library(randomForest)
train <- read_csv("../titanic_train.csv")
  1. Which variables do you think may be good predictors of the survival on the Titanic? Create two or three graphs similar to those in lab 11 (the data exploration lab). (Hint1: You may want to turn the Survived variable into a factor using the factor() function. Hint2: You may want to add + geom_jitter() to plots involving qualitative variables.)
train$Survived <- factor(train$Survived)
train$Sex <- factor(train$Sex)
ggplot(train, aes(x=Age, y=Sex, color=Survived)) + geom_point()  + geom_jitter()
## Warning: Removed 177 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

## Warning: Removed 177 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

In the above plot I look simultaneously on the effects of gender and age. Clearly, women were much more likely to survive. As for age, it does not appear that younger passengers were any more likely to survive.

ggplot(train, aes(x=Age, y=Pclass, color=Survived)) + geom_point()  + geom_jitter()
## Warning: Removed 177 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

## Warning: Removed 177 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

In the above plot I look at the effect of passenger class and age. It is clear that survival was much less likely among passengers in the third class. Also, it appears that children in the first and particularly in the second class were much more likely to survive than children in the third class.

ggplot(train, aes(x=Sex, y=Pclass, color=Survived)) + geom_point()  + geom_jitter()

Again, the picture shows the effect of class. Women in first and second class mostly survived whereas those in the third class did not.

  1. Estimate a decision tree predicting survival using age and sex as predictors. Describe your results.
tree <- rpart(Survived ~ Age + Sex, data=train)
rpart.plot(tree)

The algorithm says that women survive. Men survive if they are 6.5 years old or younger.

  1. Estimate a decision tree using age, sex and passenger class. Describe your results.
tree <- rpart(Survived ~ Age + Sex + Pclass, data=train, minsplit=50)
rpart.plot(tree)

Again, men died unless they were boys younger than 6 and a half. Women in first and second class survived. Women in third class died unless they were younger than 28.

  1. Estimate your own decision tree with your own set of predictors (you are, of course, free to include the predictors we used above).
tree <- rpart(Survived ~ Age + Sex + Pclass + SibSp + Parch , data=train, minsplit=60)
rpart.plot(tree)

Again, men died unless they were boys younger than 6 and a half. Women in first and second class survived. Women in third class died unless they had at most one parent or child on board. (Women in third class who had more than 1 parent or child on board died. Perhaps, larger families tried to stay together and ended up dying.)

  1. Download titanic_test.csv from Nexus. This is a test data from Kaggle. It has information on 418 passengers except we actually dont know whether they survived or not. Use your favorite model from above to predict which of these passengers survived. Show your predictions for the first 6 passengers.
test <- read_csv("https://www.dropbox.com/s/x7vt6nrankfj0kz/titanic_test.csv?raw=1")
test$Sex <- as.factor(test$Sex)
test$Survived_pred <- predict(tree, test, type="class")
table(test$Survived_pred)

  1. Even though we dont know the fate of the passengers in the test data set, Kaggle does. In fact, Kaggle will evaluate our predictions and tell us how many we got right. Moreover, Kaggle will compare the accuracy of our predictions to those of other participants in the competition. All we have to do is register with Kaggle and create a .csv file that contains two columns: PassengerId and Survived, where Survived contains our predictions: 0 for did not survive, and 1 for survived. You can use write_csv() to make that .csv file (make sure to select() only PassengerId and Survived. Submit your predictions to Kaggle and report on your accuracy and rank compared to other participants. You can make up to 5 submissions per day if you would like to experiment with different models, and improve your submission. Feel free to try randomForest. Take a screenshot of your submission result, and attach it to your lab. I will pay five dollars to the team with the highest rank. Good luck!
train$Age <- ifelse(is.na(train$Age), mean(train$Age, na.rm = TRUE), train$Age)
test$Age <- ifelse(is.na(test$Age), mean(test$Age, na.rm = TRUE), test$Age)
rf <- randomForest(Survived ~ Age + Sex + Pclass + Parch + SibSp , data=train, na.action=na.omit)
test$Survived <- predict(rf, test, type="class")
write_csv(select(test, PassengerId, Survived), "Submission.csv")

The above model generated accuracy of 77.511% on the test data, which as of February 4 ranks in the 5,000s.
